                value:
                  'The ability to emotionally communicate with voters is crucial to the success of any political campaign. It is an effective strategy for encouraging people to connect emotionally with a legislator, which can increase voter turnout. Longer advertisements are more likely to induce the social-relational emotion known as the kama muta theory if they tell a story and praise one candidate. According to this theory, increased prosocial and altruistic behaviour can result from increased community sharing, such as a threatened communal relationship. Attack advertisements, on the other hand, rely heavily on wrath to motivate viewers to dislike either the current situation or their political opponent.',
